By the limit definition of the derivative of $f$ at
$x$,\begin{align*}
f'(x) &= \lim_{h \to 0}\frac{f(x+h) - f(x)}{h}
\\ &= \lim_{h \to 0}\frac{\frac{x+h}{2(x+h)+1} - \frac{x}{2x+1}}{h}
\\ &= \lim_{h \to 0}\frac{(x+h)(2x+1) -x(2(x+h)+1)}{h(2(x+h)+1)(2x+1)} 
\\ &= \lim_{h \to 0}\frac{(2x^2 + x + 2xh + h) - (2x^2 + 2xh + x)}{h(2(x+h)+1)(2x+1)} 
\\ &= \lim_{h \to 0}\frac{h}{h(2(x+h)+1)(2x+1)} 
\\ &= \lim_{h \to 0}\frac{1}{(2(x+h)+1)(2x+1)} 
\\ &= \frac{1}{(2(x+0)+1)(2x+1)} 
\\ &= {\color{blue} \frac{1}{(2x+1)^2}}\end{align*}

Use of the quotient rule confirms that this is indeed
$\displaystyle f'(x)$:\begin{align*}
f'(x) &= \frac{1 \cdot (2x+1) - x \cdot 2}{(2x+1)^2}
\\ &= {\color{OliveGreen} \frac{1}{(2x+1)^2}}\end{align*}

By the alternative limit definition of the derivative of $f$ at
$a$,\begin{align*}
f'(a) &= \lim_{x \to a}\frac{f(x) - f(a)}{x-a}
\\ &= \lim_{x \to a}\frac{\frac{x}{2x+1} - \frac{a}{2a+1}}{x-a}
\\ &= \lim_{x \to a}\frac{\frac{x(2a+1) - a(2x+1)}{(2x+1)(2a+1)}}{x-a} 
\\ &= \lim_{x \to a}\frac{\frac{(2ax+x) - (2ax+a)}{(2x+1)(2a+1)}}{x-a} 
\\ &= \lim_{x \to a}\frac{\frac{x - a}{(2x+1)(2a+1)}}{x-a} 
\\ &= \lim_{x \to a}\frac{1}{(2x+1)(2a+1)} 
\\ &= \frac{1}{(2a+1)^2} 
\\ f'(x) &= {\color{blue} \frac{1}{(2x+1)^2}}\end{align*}

Use of the quotient rule confirms that this is indeed
$\displaystyle f'(x)$:\begin{align*}
f'(x) &= \frac{1 \cdot (2x+1) - x \cdot 2}{(2x+1)^2}
\\ &= {\color{OliveGreen} \frac{1}{(2x+1)^2}}\end{align*}
